<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://theeventscalendar.com/disable-gutenberg-keep-wordpress-classic-editor/">But Iâ€™m Not Ready! How to Disable Gutenberg and Keep the Classic WordPress Editor</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://theeventscalendar.com">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>
";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3:"Jen";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9551:"<p>With the release of WordPress 5.0 and the new Gutenberg block editor right around the corner, many people have asked: <strong>If Iâ€™m not ready, how can I keep the classic editor on my WordPress site? </strong></p>
<p>While the Gutenberg editor offers an exciting new post and page editing experience (<a href="http://theeventscalendar.com/content-creation-gutenberg-block-editor">especially for content creators</a>), itâ€™s understandable that you might want more time to get familiar with the block editor and test things out before going live.</p>
<blockquote><p>Not familiar with the block editor yet? Snag our free <a href="https://theeventscalendar.com/gutenberg-block-editor-free-ebook/">Guide to Gutenberg ebook</a>!</p></blockquote>
<p>Lucky for you, itâ€™s easy to disable Gutenberg until youâ€™re ready for it and keep the classic editor on your WordPress site. You can disable the block editor entirely or selectively phase it inâ€”the choice is entirely yours.</p>
<h2>First Things First: Make a Backup!</h2>
<p>We canâ€™t stress this enough. If you donâ€™t have a complete backup of your site and database, go make one now. While the odds of anything going awry when updating to WordPress 5.0 are pretty low, itâ€™s still possible something could break on your site. Trust usâ€”if something does go wrong, youâ€™ll be so glad you took the extra couple of minutes to make a good backup.</p>
<p>If youâ€™ve never done this before, take a second to learn how to <a href="https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/creating-site-backups/">create a site backup</a>. We also recommend testing updates on a staging site before pushing them to your live site. If you donâ€™t already have one, you can use our <a href="https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/creating-using-wordpress-staging-site/">staging site setup guide</a> to get started.</p>
<h2>Disable Gutenberg with the Classic Editor Plugin</h2>
<p>If youâ€™re not ready for the block editor when WordPress 5.0 arrives, you can install the <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/classic-editor/">Classic Editor plugin</a> (developed by core WordPress contributors) to keep using the classic editor until you feel comfortable switching over.</p>
<p>This plugin offers two options:</p>
<ul>
<li>Disable the Gutenberg block editor entirely</li>
<li>Configure settings to keep both Gutenberg and the classic editor active</li>
</ul>
<p>At the time of writing, the core Gutenberg development team is considering whether or not the Classic Editor plugin should be included by default with WordPress 5.0 update. For the latest updates, head over to our <a href="https://theeventscalendar.com/gutenberg-block-editor-news/">All Things Gutenberg resource page</a>.</p>
<h2>Selectively Activate Using the Gutenberg Ramp Plugin</h2>
<p>Adapting your site to the new Gutenberg block editor doesnâ€™t have to be all or nothing. The folks at Automattic, the team behind WordPress.com and WordPress VIP, have created a helpful tool called the <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/gutenberg-ramp/">Gutenberg Ramp</a> plugin.</p>
<p>With this plugin, you can activate the WordPress block editor selectively across your siteâ€”for example, you can choose to activate the block editor only on specific post types (such as events).</p>
<h2>What Happens Next?</h2>
<p>The core WordPress team <a href="https://make.wordpress.org/core/2018/11/07/classic-editor-plugin-support-window/">has confirmed</a> the Classic Editor plugin will be officially supported until December 31, 2021, and we expect the Gutenberg Ramp plugin will follow a similar timeline.</p>
<p>While you can certainly stick with the classic editor for as long as you need, you wonâ€™t want to wait too long to make the switch. New, exciting features are already being developed around the block editorâ€”the sooner you make the transition, the sooner youâ€™ll be able to put those features to work on your site.</p>
<p>Embracing the Gutenberg block editor can seem intimidating at first, but remember, you donâ€™t have to tackle it all at once. Armed with a smart plan for your site and helpful resources like the ones on our <a href="https://theeventscalendar.com/gutenberg-block-editor-news/">All Things Gutenberg page</a>, youâ€™ll be able to gracefully navigate the changes at your own pace.</p>
<p><em>Get the latest Gutenberg info and other news from The Events Calendar delivered straight to your inbox.</em></p>

